            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I think we can do this and also leverage the improvement in TUI: #6619 will introduce a \"compositor\" layer which will translate from new external UI representations (at first only floating windows on separate screen grids) back to the current TUI-compatible protocol. This compositor could of course also merge new highlighting layers such as separately rendered cursorline/column, and update the TUI screen without needing to do a slow full redraw (`win_update`/`win_line`)\r\n\r\nYes, it is an \"inner plattform\" to some extent but I think a justified one:\r\n\r\n- Adding this directly to tui.c would mean the new feature won't be supported on older GUI:s that haven't opted in to the functionality.\r\n- Anything to this effect can  in principle be done directly in screen.c, but adding a new module with will be more open to experimentation than making `win_update`, `win_line`, etc even more complicated than it is. \r\n- It will be possible to attach multiple UIs (including the TUI) with different features active at the same time, unlike today where we default to the most restrictive subset of requested features.",
